				<li id="16095976" class="cmnt-root" data="13" data-d="1550677015000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><div class="comment-username">Anonymous</div></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t530353/Divine-Blessing" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">20 Feb 2019 10:36</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=165&p=16095976" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">If we&apos;re going off the english translation, it&apos;s canon that the queen of lothric was Gwynevere. It pretty explicitly says that the queen was &quot;initially revered as a goddess of fertility and bounty&quot;, Gwynevere&apos;s own spheres of influence as stated in the item description of the divine blessing in Ds1. The argument of the japanese translation applies both ways, you can say the translation &quot;might be wrong&quot; and point out that japanese to english is an iffy business, but you can day the same back. The english translation might&apos;ve been what they were going for in the original japanese text or it could&apos;ve been the only way TO accurately translate it to english. Either way, time leans towards that the english translation was right, the item description wasn&apos;t patched. You could argue that it&apos;s her daughter, but there is no proof. It was never said any of her daughters were worshipped.</p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16095976" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggl